      Purdue
   =20
 =20

Purdue Pharma is a corporation that makes and sells opioid painkillers.
  [1]
 It did this in various bad ways that helped create an opioid addiction epi=
demic, and it has been sued by various victims of that epidemic for trillio=
ns of dollars. The value of Purdue =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, mostly, the pres=
ent value of its continuing cash flows from selling more opioids =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0is much less than the value of those claims.
  [2]
=C2=A0So Purdue filed for bankruptcy, and the resolution of the bankruptcy =
case involves essentially handing over Purdue (to be renamed =E2=80=9CKnoa =
Pharma=E2=80=9D) to the representatives of its victims: It will sell opioid=
s and give the profits to the victims of its previous opioid sales efforts,=
 though hopefully the future efforts will be more careful.
But Purdue Pharma was historically mostly owned by the Sackler family, and =
various Sacklers were deeply involved in its decisions to make and sell opi=
oid painkillers. Purdue also paid roughly $11 billion=C2=A0of dividends to =
the Sacklers over the years, considerably more than Purdue/Knoa is worth no=
w.=C2=A0
From first principles, it does not seem fair for the Sacklers to run a comp=
any with largely negative social effects (it made billions of dollars of pr=
ofits but caused, allegedly, trillions of dollars of damages),=C2=A0extract=
 the billions of dollars of profits for themselves, and then hand over the =
company to the victims and say =E2=80=9Cfine, it=E2=80=99s your opioid comp=
any now.=E2=80=9D Shouldn=E2=80=99t they have to give back the profits?
From second principles, that is just the way limited liability works: The e=
ntity selling the opioids was a corporation, and corporations have limited =
liability. The shareholders of a corporation are not personally responsible=
 for the debts of the corporation; the worst that can happen to them is tha=
t their stock goes to zero. The Sacklers=E2=80=99 stock will go to zero in =
the bankruptcy =E2=80=94=C2=A0they will hand over Purdue/Knoa to its credit=
ors =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the rest of their billions are off-limits to the Pur=
due bankruptcy court.
From third principles, there are lots of exceptions to limited liability. I=
f the Sacklers got big dividends while Purdue was insolvent, a bankruptcy c=
ourt could claw those back. If the Sacklers, as directors and officers of P=
urdue, made decisions to break the law, they could be sued for those decisi=
ons =E2=80=94=C2=A0by Purdue itself,
  [3]
=C2=A0for breaching their fiduciary duties, or by its victims or by various=
 governments =E2=80=94=C2=A0and have to pay their personal money to resolve=
 those lawsuits. And the realities=C2=A0of the situation =E2=80=94=C2=A0the=
 Sacklers are high-profile billionaires with their names (formerly) on lots=
 of cultural institutions, the opioid epidemic is huge, the remaining value=
 of Purdue/Knoa is small compared to the enormous damages =E2=80=94=C2=A0me=
an that it would make sense for lots of people (victims, governments) to go=
 after various Sacklers personally on various theories of liability.
From fourth principles, the Sacklers are international billionaires who can=
 and did hire good lawyers, so a lot of their money is going to be pretty s=
afe from those sorts of lawsuits, both in the sense that they might have pl=
ausible defenses to those lawsuits and in the sense that a lot of the money=
 is locked up in foreign trusts where courts probably can=E2=80=99t get it.
And so one might want a compromise. The compromise is:
=09The victims get Purdue/Knoa, sure. That=E2=80=99s just obvious; that=E2=
=80=99s the norm of corporate bankruptcy.=09The Sacklers=C2=A0also=C2=A0chi=
p in billions of dollars of their own money to pay the victims: They do not=
 get all of the benefits of limited liability.=09But the Sacklers also=C2=
=A0keep lots of money: They get=C2=A0a lot=C2=A0of the benefits of limited =
liability; in particular, their liability is limited. They are on the hook =
for some of Purdue=E2=80=99s debts, beyond just handing over the corporate =
stock. But they are not on the hook for Purdue=E2=80=99s debts to the full =
extent of their personal wealth; they walk away from Purdue and remain rich=
.

You don=E2=80=99t have to like it! That=E2=80=99s why it=E2=80=99s a compro=
mise. It is much better for victims than getting=C2=A0nothing=C2=A0from the=
 Sacklers, and much better for the Sacklers than paying=C2=A0everything, an=
d both of those are, in principle, realistic possibilities.
This is in fact the compromise that was reached in the bankruptcy case: Rep=
resentatives of the victims and of the Sacklers went to mediation and agree=
d that the victims would get basically Purdue/Knoa plus $4.375 billion of m=
oney from the Sacklers. And they agreed that, as part of the compromise, no=
body=C2=A0would be allowed to sue the Sacklers for how they ran Purdue: The=
  bankruptcy plan =E2=80=9Ccontained several nonconsensual releases =E2=80=
=A6 that, in effect, permanently enjoined certain third-party claims agains=
t the Sacklers.=E2=80=9D
  [4]

A bankruptcy judge approved this plan, which was also approved by a large m=
ajority of the victims. But some victims and some governments objected and =
appealed to the district court, arguing that the bankruptcy court is not al=
lowed to give those =E2=80=9Cthird-party releases=E2=80=9D: Purdue=E2=80=99=
s bankruptcy can resolve all claims against Purdue, they argued, but the Sa=
cklers weren=E2=80=99t in bankruptcy, so the bankruptcy court was not allow=
ed to close off all lawsuits against them. The counter-argument is basicall=
y (1) bankruptcy courts have lots of broad general powers to order things t=
o get=C2=A0their bankruptcy cases resolved fairly and (2) without the relea=
ses, there=E2=80=99s no Sackler money for victims. The Sacklers agreed to c=
hip in money to get the releases; they agreed to some personal liability in=
 exchange for avoiding unlimited personal liability.
In late 2021, the district court overturned the plan, finding that the bank=
ruptcy court was not allowed to give the releases. We   talked about it at =
the time. I was skeptical; I wrote:

It is not at all clear that=C2=A0the bankruptcy plan=C2=A0is what is shield=
ing the Sacklers=E2=80=99 personal assets. One=C2=A0reason the bankruptcy p=
lan released=C2=A0the Sacklers from liability, and the bankruptcy judge app=
roved it, is that=C2=A0their assets were probably already shielded, in offs=
hore spendthrift trusts that creditors probably couldn=E2=80=99t touch. Tha=
t does seem bad! But getting rid of third-party releases in bankruptcy does=
n=E2=80=99t fix it.
And note that the result of this ruling is not that they go back to the neg=
otiating table and the Sacklers kick in, you know, $8 billion instead of $4=
.5 billion. The result of this ruling is that the whole settlement framewor=
k is illegal, and the bankruptcy court can=E2=80=99t cut off lawsuits again=
st the Sacklers for any amount of money.=C2=A0

Well. Since then, two things happened. One is that they went back to the ne=
gotiating table and the Sacklers agreed to kick in =E2=80=9Can additional $=
1.175=E2=80=93$1.675 billion,=E2=80=9D for a total of up to $6 billion of S=
ackler money; this increased contribution won over some (though not all) of=
 the victims who had objected to the previous settlement.=C2=A0
The other is that Purdue appealed to the US Court of Appeals for the Second=
 Circuit to try to get the district court=E2=80=99s=C2=A0ruling reversed. Y=
esterday it won.=C2=A0The  Second Circuit ruled that the bankruptcy court i=
s allowed to release the Sacklers from liability, and also that it was a go=
od idea here:
We conclude that two sections of the Bankruptcy Code, 11 U.S.C. =C2=A7=C2=
=A7 105(a), 1123(b)(6), jointly provide the statutory basis for the bankrup=
tcy court=E2=80=99s authority=C2=A0to approve a plan that includes nonconse=
nsual releases of third-party claims against non-debtors. In addition, this=
 Court has recognized that in specific=C2=A0circumstances=E2=80=94such as t=
hose presented by this appeal=E2=80=94bankruptcy courts are permitted to ap=
prove of restructuring plans that include such releases. We=C2=A0accordingl=
y hold that the bankruptcy court=E2=80=99s approval of the releases here is=
 8 permissible both statutorily and under this Court=E2=80=99s case law. We=
 further hold that=C2=A0the bankruptcy court=E2=80=99s inclusion of the rel=
eases is equitable and appropriate under the specific factual circumstances=
 of this case, and we articulate several factors to guide the analysis as t=
o when to allow similar releases in reorganization plans.
There is an eight-factor test for deciding when to give these releases, tho=
ugh I will just mention two factors. One is =E2=80=9Cthe factually and lega=
lly intertwined nature of the claims against both the Debtors and the Sackl=
ers=E2=80=9D: The reason=C2=A0anyone would be suing the Sacklers would be b=
ecause of stuff that Purdue did, or that they did through Purdue; resolving=
 those claims in Purdue=E2=80=99s bankruptcy makes some rough sense.
The other is that =E2=80=9Cthe Releases are essential to reorganization,=E2=
=80=9D mainly because, decades ago,=C2=A0Purdue agreed to indemnify the Sac=
klers for Purdue-related claims against them. And so if someone sued the Sa=
cklers today for things that Purdue did, Purdue would technically be on the=
 hook to pay the damages; that is, the Sacklers would have a claim against =
the bankruptcy estate. The third-party releases are a way to deal with that=
 uncertain claim (by getting rid of it), and so they help resolve the bankr=
uptcy case and get the victims paid.
You still don=E2=80=99t have to like it! (And the district court=E2=80=99s =
decision, though it did not have the=C2=A0intent=C2=A0of extracting an extr=
a billion from the Sacklers, did have that=C2=A0effect.) But it seems like =
a reasonable outcome, a compromise between the general idea that corporate =
shareholders get limited liability and the specific intuition that opioid-c=
ompany controlling shareholders maybe shouldn=E2=80=99t.

