      Are annuities bank accounts?
   =20
 =20

Conceptually, there are three main ways to finance a portfolio of long-term=
 bonds
  [5]
:
=09You can be a=C2=A0bank. You take money (=E2=80=9Cdeposits=E2=80=9D) from=
 customers, and you tell the customers they can get back exactly as much mo=
ney as they put in, whenever they want. Then you use the money to buy long-=
term bonds, which pay interest; you keep most of the interest but give the =
customers some of it. If interest rates go up, the value of your bonds will=
 go down; if you take $100 of deposits and buy $100 of bonds and rates go u=
p and the bonds are worth $90, you will not have enough bonds to pay out ev=
eryone if they all ask for their money back at once. You hope this won=E2=
=80=99t happen, and there is lots of banking regulation and supervision to =
prevent it, but bank runs are the well-known risk of banking: If everyone t=
akes their money out at once, there is not enough money for them.=C2=A0=09Y=
ou can be a=C2=A0mutual fund. You take money from customers and you use it =
to buy bonds. You tell the customers they can take money out whenever they =
want, but they get back only (their share of) the current market value of t=
he bonds. If you take $100 of money and buy $100 of bonds and rates go up a=
nd the bonds are worth $90 and customers take their money out, you will giv=
e them $90. They will not complain: This is the thing they signed up for. M=
utual funds are not really subject to run risk. People do still worry about=
 runs on mutual funds, in part for somewhat fuzzy reasons =E2=80=94=C2=A0I =
used to make fun of it as =E2=80=9Cpeople are worried about bond market liq=
uidity=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in part because, sure, if everyone asks =
for their money back at once, mutual funds will have to sell bonds and that=
 will drive the prices of bonds down. But there is no real advantage to ask=
ing for your money back=C2=A0first=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0you just get the mar=
ket price =E2=80=94=C2=A0so they are considerably safer from runs.=09You ca=
n have=C2=A0locked-up capital. You take money from customers and you use it=
 to buy bonds. You tell the customers that they can=E2=80=99t take their mo=
ney out for a long time, and you use that long-term locked-up money to make=
 long-term investments and not worry about fluctuations in their market val=
ue. You take $100 of money and buy $100 of bonds and wait until the bonds m=
ature and then give investors back their $100 (with interest). If interest =
rates go up and the market value of the bonds drops to $90, that is just no=
t=C2=A0relevant to you: You don=E2=80=99t have to sell the bonds, because y=
our financing is locked up, and when they mature they will pay out $100.

We have talked a lot this year about the problems of Category 1; there have=
 been bank runs.   One broad   problem here is   that banks tend not to=C2=
=A0think=C2=A0of their =E2=80=9Cdeposit franchise=E2=80=9D this way, as sho=
rt-term money that can be withdrawn at any time. Banks think that they have=
 built long-term relationships with information-insensitive customers who a=
re not looking to withdraw money the moment interest rates go up; they thin=
k that they have long-term financing for behavioral=C2=A0reasons (their cus=
tomers mostly don=E2=80=99t take their money out) rather than=C2=A0contract=
ual=C2=A0ones (their customers=C2=A0can=C2=A0take their money out). Or at l=
east, they used to think that. This year may have changed some minds.
Meanwhile I tend to think of the insurance business as=C2=A0mostly Category=
 3: In life insurance, mostly what happens is that people give you money ev=
ery month and you use it to buy bonds and you don=E2=80=99t pay them back u=
ntil they die. In annuities, mostly what happens is that people give you mo=
ney and you use it to buy bonds and you pay them money=C2=A0on a long fixed=
 schedule until they die. Insurance has pretty permanent capital, which mak=
es it a   much better funding source for, say, bank loans than banks are.
But here is a Wall Street Journal article titled =E2=80=9CThere Were Runs o=
n Banks, Not on Insurers. Here=E2=80=99s Why.=E2=80=9D Well, because banks =
are runnable and insurance companies are not, seems like the intuitive answ=
er to me, but there is some nuance there. In fact annuity holders=C2=A0can=
=C2=A0cash out early, but they mostly don=E2=80=99t:

As interest rates shot up from near-zero, dramatically improving the return=
s on new annuities, investors mostly stayed in their existing policies, new=
 data show. =E2=80=A6
Surrenders, or early cash-outs, from fixed-rate deferred annuities ticked u=
p only modestly last year, rising to 8% of assets compared with 7% for 2021=
, according to industry-funded research firm Limra. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CSo far at least, surrender experience is running favorably [for th=
e industry] compared to what you would expect in an environment where inter=
est rates have increased this much,=E2=80=9D said Douglas Baker, director o=
f North American life insurance at ratings firm Fitch Ratings.

And some of this is due to the same sorts=C2=A0of behavioral and franchise-=
y reasons that banks used to talk about before this March:

Annuity holders typically don=E2=80=99t closely follow financial markets, i=
ndustry insiders say.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think people really are doing the math on the insu=
rance side,=E2=80=9D said Greg Parady, a Florida-based financial adviser. =
=E2=80=9CMy consumers are typically retired folk [who] find something they =
like and stick with it.=E2=80=9D
Apollo=E2=80=99s [Marc] Rowan said on the earnings call the bank-run risk d=
oesn=E2=80=99t hurt the annuities industry because people use these investm=
ents to save for retirement. =E2=80=9CThis is not money they think is acces=
sible,=E2=80=9D he added.

=E2=80=9CWe keep our cheap short-term financing because our customers do no=
t pay attention to interest rates or think of themselves as rational econom=
ic actors=E2=80=9D is kind of an alarming thing to say! It=E2=80=99s kind o=
f what Silicon Valley Bank told itself! But, no, the main reasons are not b=
ehavioral but straightforwardly contractual:=C2=A0

Many investors simply don=E2=80=99t have an option to cash out. Almost a fi=
fth, or 18.5%, of money in annuities is held in contracts with no surrender=
 option, data for last year from ratings firm AM Best data show.=C2=A0
Even if surrenders are allowed, there is often a price to pay. Annuities ty=
pically impose a charge of up to 7% for withdrawing more than a certain amo=
unt during the first years of the contract. There is often no penalty for w=
ithdrawing money from a bank account.

Yes right if you can=E2=80=99t take money out of your annuity, that makes i=
t very good long-term=C2=A0financing for your insurer. If you can take mone=
y out, but have to pay 7% on the way out, that=C2=A0helps, though I suppose=
 there is some level of interest-rate changes where you=E2=80=99d do it any=
way.=C2=A0Also, even if you can withdraw money, you often withdraw it at ma=
rket value (Category 2, like a mutual fund) rather than face value (Categor=
y 1, like a bank account), which also makes runs less likely:
Investors may face another cost buried in the annuity small print: the so-c=
alled market value adjustment. When investors surrender an annuity with one=
 of these adjustments, the return is adjusted to reflect changes in the val=
ue of the underlying bonds since the contract was bought.=C2=A0
So the answer is mostly that there was no run on life insurers because life=
 insurers have structured their business not to be runnable.

