<td class=3D"body-component__content" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; m=
so-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt; line-height: 150%; padding: 0 =
10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Purdue</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Purdue Pharma is a corporation that makes and =
sells opioid painkillers.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> It did this in various bad ways that helped create an opioid addiction=
 epidemic, and it has been sued by various victims of that epidemic for tri=
llions of dollars. The value of Purdue =E2=80=94=C2=A0that is, mostly, the =
present value of its continuing cash flows from selling more opioids =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0is much less than the value of those claims.<a class=3D"footnote-i=
ndex" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !=
important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-b=
ottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; dis=
play: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0So Purdue filed for bankruptcy, and the resolution of the bankrup=
tcy case involves essentially handing over Purdue (to be renamed =E2=80=9CK=
noa Pharma=E2=80=9D) to the representatives of its victims: It will sell op=
ioids and give the profits to the victims of its previous opioid sales effo=
rts, though hopefully the future efforts will be more careful.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Purdue Pharma was historically mostly owne=
d by the Sackler family, and various Sacklers were deeply involved in its d=
ecisions to make and sell opioid painkillers. Purdue also paid roughly $11 =
billion=C2=A0of dividends to the Sacklers over the years, considerably more=
 than Purdue/Knoa is worth now.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From first principles, it does not seem fair f=
or the Sacklers to run a company with largely negative social effects (it m=
ade billions of dollars of profits but caused, allegedly, trillions of doll=
ars of damages),=C2=A0extract the billions of dollars of profits for themse=
lves, and then hand over the company to the victims and say =E2=80=9Cfine, =
it=E2=80=99s your opioid company now.=E2=80=9D Shouldn=E2=80=99t they have =
to give back the profits?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From second principles, that is just the way l=
imited liability works: The entity selling the opioids was a corporation, a=
nd corporations have limited liability. The shareholders of a corporation a=
re not personally responsible for the debts of the corporation; the worst t=
hat can happen to them is that their stock goes to zero. The Sacklers=E2=80=
=99 stock will go to zero in the bankruptcy =E2=80=94=C2=A0they will hand o=
ver Purdue/Knoa to its creditors =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the rest of their billi=
ons are off-limits to the Purdue bankruptcy court.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From third principles, there are lots of excep=
tions to limited liability. If the Sacklers got big dividends while Purdue =
was insolvent, a bankruptcy court could claw those back. If the Sacklers, a=
s directors and officers of Purdue, made decisions to break the law, they c=
ould be sued for those decisions =E2=80=94=C2=A0by Purdue itself,<a class=
=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !=
important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0for breaching their fiduciary duties, or by its victims or by var=
ious governments =E2=80=94=C2=A0and have to pay their personal money to res=
olve those lawsuits. And the realities=C2=A0of the situation =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0the Sacklers are high-profile billionaires with their names (formerly) o=
n lots of cultural institutions, the opioid epidemic is huge, the remaining=
 value of Purdue/Knoa is small compared to the enormous damages =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0mean that it would make sense for lots of people (victims, government=
s) to go after various Sacklers personally on various theories of liability=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">From fourth principles, the Sacklers are inter=
national billionaires who can and did hire good lawyers, so a lot of their =
money is going to be pretty safe from those sorts of lawsuits, both in the =
sense that they might have plausible defenses to those lawsuits and in the =
sense that a lot of the money is locked up in foreign trusts where courts p=
robably can=E2=80=99t get it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so one might want a compromise. The compro=
mise is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The victims get Purdue/Knoa, sure. Th=
at=E2=80=99s just obvious; that=E2=80=99s the norm of corporate bankruptcy.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The Sacklers=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0<=
/em>chip in billions of dollars of their own money to pay the victims: They=
 do not get all of the benefits of limited liability.</li>=09<li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">But the Sacklers also=C2=A0<em>keep </em>lots of money:=
 They get=C2=A0<em>a lot=C2=A0</em>of the benefits of limited liability; in=
 particular, their liability <em>is limited</em>. They are on the hook for =
some of Purdue=E2=80=99s debts, beyond just handing over the corporate stoc=
k. But they are not on the hook for Purdue=E2=80=99s debts to the full exte=
nt of their personal wealth; they walk away from Purdue and remain rich.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You don=E2=80=99t have to like it! That=E2=80=
=99s why it=E2=80=99s a compromise. It is much better for victims than gett=
ing=C2=A0<em>nothing=C2=A0</em>from the Sacklers, and much better for the S=
acklers than paying=C2=A0<em>everything</em>, and both of those are, in pri=
nciple, realistic possibilities.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is in fact the compromise that was reache=
d in the bankruptcy case: Representatives of the victims and of the Sackler=
s went to mediation and agreed that the victims would get basically Purdue/=
Knoa plus $4.375 billion of money from the Sacklers. And they agreed that, =
as part of the compromise, <em>nobody=C2=A0</em>would be allowed to sue the=
 Sacklers for how they ran Purdue: The <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/31650686.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2EyLnVzY291cnRzLmdvdi=
9kZWNpc2lvbnMvaXN5c3F1ZXJ5LzFlNjVhNjM1LTI0MzQtNDBhMi1hYjdkLWU2NDMzMmM5YTQ4Y=
i8xL2RvYy8yMi0xMTBfY29tcGxldGVfb3BuLnBkZiN4bWw9aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2EyLnVzY291=
cnRzLmdvdi9kZWNpc2lvbnMvaXN5c3F1ZXJ5LzFlNjVhNjM1LTI0MzQtNDBhMi1hYjdkLWU2NDM=
zMmM5YTQ4Yi8xL2hpbGl0ZS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6606d15f" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; =
text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-c=
olor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> bankru=
ptcy plan</a> =E2=80=9Ccontained several nonconsensual releases =E2=80=A6 t=
hat, in effect, permanently enjoined certain third-party claims against the=
 Sacklers.=E2=80=9D<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A bankruptcy judge approved this plan, which w=
as also approved by a large majority of the victims. But some victims and s=
ome governments objected and appealed to the district court, arguing that t=
he bankruptcy court is not allowed to give those =E2=80=9Cthird-party relea=
ses=E2=80=9D: Purdue=E2=80=99s bankruptcy can resolve all claims against Pu=
rdue, they argued, but the Sacklers weren=E2=80=99t in bankruptcy, so the b=
ankruptcy court was not allowed to close off all lawsuits against <em>them.=
 </em>The counter-argument is basically (1) bankruptcy courts have lots of =
broad general powers to order things to get=C2=A0their bankruptcy cases res=
olved fairly and (2) without the releases, there=E2=80=99s no Sackler money=
 for victims. The Sacklers agreed to chip in money to get the releases; the=
y agreed to some personal liability in exchange for avoiding unlimited pers=
onal liability.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In late 2021, the district court overturned th=
e plan, finding that the bankruptcy court was not allowed to give the relea=
ses. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31650686.2=
59419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTItM=
jMvdGhlLXB1cmR1ZS1iYW5rcnVwdGN5LWRpZG4tdC13b3JrP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MzEyM19NT05F=
WVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI=
zMDUzMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6c3a163d" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">  talked about it at the time</a>. I was skeptical; I wrote:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is not at all clear that=C2=A0<em>the bankr=
uptcy plan=C2=A0</em>is what is shielding the Sacklers=E2=80=99 personal as=
sets. One=C2=A0reason the bankruptcy plan released=C2=A0the Sacklers from l=
iability, and the bankruptcy judge approved it, is that=C2=A0<em>their asse=
ts were probably already shielded</em>, in offshore spendthrift trusts that=
 creditors probably couldn=E2=80=99t touch. That does seem bad! But getting=
 rid of third-party releases in bankruptcy doesn=E2=80=99t fix it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And note that the result of this ruling is not=
 that they go back to the negotiating table and the Sacklers kick in, you k=
now, $8 billion instead of $4.5 billion. The result of this ruling is that =
the whole settlement framework is illegal, and the bankruptcy court can=E2=
=80=99t cut off lawsuits against the Sacklers for any amount of money.=C2=
=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well. Since then, two things happened. One is =
that they went back to the negotiating table and the Sacklers agreed to kic=
k in =E2=80=9Can additional $1.175=E2=80=93$1.675 billion,=E2=80=9D for a t=
otal of up to $6 billion of Sackler money; this increased contribution won =
over some (though not all) of the victims who had objected to the previous =
settlement.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other is that Purdue appealed to the US Co=
urt of Appeals for the Second Circuit to try to get the district court=E2=
=80=99s=C2=A0ruling reversed. Yesterday it won.=C2=A0The <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31650686.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY2Ey=
LnVzY291cnRzLmdvdi9kZWNpc2lvbnMvaXN5c3F1ZXJ5LzFlNjVhNjM1LTI0MzQtNDBhMi1hYjd=
kLWU2NDMzMmM5YTQ4Yi8xL2RvYy8yMi0xMTBfY29tcGxldGVfb3BuLnBkZiN4bWw9aHR0cHM6Ly=
93d3cuY2EyLnVzY291cnRzLmdvdi9kZWNpc2lvbnMvaXN5c3F1ZXJ5LzFlNjVhNjM1LTI0MzQtN=
DBhMi1hYjdkLWU2NDMzMmM5YTQ4Yi8xL2hpbGl0ZS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC6606d15=
f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> Second Circuit ruled</a> that the bankruptcy court is allowed=
 to release the Sacklers from liability, and also that it was a good idea h=
ere:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We conclude that two sections of t=
he Bankruptcy Code, 11 U.S.C. =C2=A7=C2=A7 105(a), 1123(b)(6), jointly prov=
ide the statutory basis for the bankruptcy court=E2=80=99s authority=C2=A0t=
o approve a plan that includes nonconsensual releases of third-party claims=
 against non-debtors. In addition, this Court has recognized that in specif=
ic=C2=A0circumstances=E2=80=94such as those presented by this appeal=E2=80=
=94bankruptcy courts are permitted to approve of restructuring plans that i=
nclude such releases. We=C2=A0accordingly hold that the bankruptcy court=E2=
=80=99s approval of the releases here is 8 permissible both statutorily and=
 under this Court=E2=80=99s case law. We further hold that=C2=A0the bankrup=
tcy court=E2=80=99s inclusion of the releases is equitable and appropriate =
under the specific factual circumstances of this case, and we articulate se=
veral factors to guide the analysis as to when to allow similar releases in=
 reorganization plans.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is an eight-factor test for deciding whe=
n to give these releases, though I will just mention two factors. One is =
=E2=80=9Cthe factually and legally intertwined nature of the claims against=
 both the Debtors and the Sacklers=E2=80=9D: The <em>reason=C2=A0</em>anyon=
e would be suing the Sacklers would be because of stuff that Purdue did, or=
 that they did through Purdue; resolving those claims in Purdue=E2=80=99s b=
ankruptcy makes some rough sense.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other is that =E2=80=9Cthe Releases are es=
sential to reorganization,=E2=80=9D mainly because, decades ago,=C2=A0Purdu=
e agreed to indemnify the Sacklers for Purdue-related claims against them. =
And so if someone sued the Sacklers today for things that Purdue did, Purdu=
e would technically be on the hook to pay the damages; that is, the Sackler=
s would have a claim against the bankruptcy estate. The third-party release=
s are a way to deal with that uncertain claim (by getting rid of it), and s=
o they help resolve the bankruptcy case and get the victims paid.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You still don=E2=80=99t have to like it! (And =
the district court=E2=80=99s decision, though it did not have the=C2=A0<em>=
intent=C2=A0</em>of extracting an extra billion from the Sacklers, did have=
 that=C2=A0<em>effect</em>.) But it seems like a reasonable outcome, a comp=
romise between the general idea that corporate shareholders get limited lia=
bility and the specific intuition that opioid-company controlling sharehold=
ers maybe shouldn=E2=80=99t.</p>
