<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Conceptually, there are three main ways to fin=
ance a portfolio of long-term bonds<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foo=
tnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none =
!important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block=
;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can be a=C2=A0<em>bank</em>. You =
take money (=E2=80=9Cdeposits=E2=80=9D) from customers, and you tell the cu=
stomers they can get back exactly as much money as they put in, whenever th=
ey want. Then you use the money to buy long-term bonds, which pay interest;=
 you keep most of the interest but give the customers some of it. If intere=
st rates go up, the value of your bonds will go down; if you take $100 of d=
eposits and buy $100 of bonds and rates go up and the bonds are worth $90, =
you will not have enough bonds to pay out everyone if they all ask for thei=
r money back at once. You hope this won=E2=80=99t happen, and there is lots=
 of banking regulation and supervision to prevent it, but bank runs are the=
 well-known risk of banking: If everyone takes their money out at once, the=
re is not enough money for them.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5=
px;">You can be a=C2=A0<em>mutual fund</em>. You take money from customers =
and you use it to buy bonds. You tell the customers they can take money out=
 whenever they want, but they get back only (their share of) the current ma=
rket value of the bonds. If you take $100 of money and buy $100 of bonds an=
d rates go up and the bonds are worth $90 and customers take their money ou=
t, you will give them $90. They will not complain: This is the thing they s=
igned up for. Mutual funds are not really subject to run risk. People do st=
ill worry about runs on mutual funds, in part for somewhat fuzzy reasons =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0I used to make fun of it as =E2=80=9Cpeople are worried abou=
t bond market liquidity=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but in part because, sure, =
if everyone asks for their money back at once, mutual funds will have to se=
ll bonds and that will drive the prices of bonds down. But there is no real=
 advantage to asking for your money back=C2=A0<em>first=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=
=C2=A0you just get the market price =E2=80=94=C2=A0so they are considerably=
 safer from runs.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You can have=C2=
=A0<em>locked-up capital</em>. You take money from customers and you use it=
 to buy bonds. You tell the customers that they can=E2=80=99t take their mo=
ney out for a long time, and you use that long-term locked-up money to make=
 long-term investments and not worry about fluctuations in their market val=
ue. You take $100 of money and buy $100 of bonds and wait until the bonds m=
ature and then give investors back their $100 (with interest). If interest =
rates go up and the market value of the bonds drops to $90, that is just no=
t=C2=A0relevant to you: You don=E2=80=99t have to sell the bonds, because y=
our financing is locked up, and when they mature they will pay out $100.</l=
i>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We have talked a lot this year about the probl=
ems of Category 1; there have been bank runs. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/31650686.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMjIvYmFua3MtZ290LXJpc2luZy1yYXRlcy13cm=
9uZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTMxMjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY=
2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MzEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f=
07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa5973e19" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscop=
e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  One</a> broad <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31650686.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDQvbm9ib2R5LXRydXN0cy10aGUtY=
mFua3Mtbm93P2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MzEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRt=
X3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUzMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHV=
