 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  problem</a> here is <a hre=
f=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31650686.259419/aHR0cHM6=
Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDkvaXQtcy1uZXZ=
lci10b28tbGF0ZS1mb3ItYmFua3MtdG8taGVkZ2U_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUzMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRk=
YmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTMxJ=
nV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB49657bfe" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  that</a> banks tend not to=C2=A0<em>think=C2=A0</em>of their =E2=80=9Cdep=
osit franchise=E2=80=9D this way, as short-term money that can be withdrawn=
 at any time. Banks think that they have built long-term relationships with=
 information-insensitive customers who are not looking to withdraw money th=
e moment interest rates go up; they think that they have long-term financin=
g for <em>behavioral=C2=A0</em>reasons (their customers mostly don=E2=80=99=
t take their money out) rather than=C2=A0<em>contractual=C2=A0</em>ones (th=
eir customers=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>take their money out). Or at least, th=
ey used to think that. This year may have changed some minds.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile I tend to think of the insurance bus=
iness as=C2=A0<em>mostly </em>Category 3: In life insurance, mostly what ha=
ppens is that people give you money every month and you use it to buy bonds=
 and you don=E2=80=99t pay them back until they die. In annuities, mostly w=
hat happens is that people give you money and you use it to buy bonds and y=
ou pay them money=C2=A0on a long fixed schedule until they die. Insurance h=
as pretty permanent capital, which makes it a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/31650686.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMTEvYmxhY2tzdG9uZS1jYW4tYmUtdGhlLWJhbm=
s_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUzMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTMxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cBa3d0ea6e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  much better funding source for, say, =
bank loans</a> than banks are.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But here is a Wall Street Journal article titl=
ed =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/316506=
86.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy90aGVyZS13ZXJlLXJ1bnMtb24tY=
mFua3Mtbm90LW9uLWluc3VyZXJzLWhlcmVzLXdoeS1jOWVlYTVmMD9tb2Q9aXRwX3dzaiZydT15=
YWhvbw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB75d08dae" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">There Were Runs on Banks=
, Not on Insurers. Here=E2=80=99s Why.</a>=E2=80=9D Well, because banks are=
 runnable and insurance companies are not, seems like the intuitive answer =
to me, but there is some nuance there. In fact annuity holders=C2=A0<em>can=
=C2=A0</em>cash out early, but they mostly don=E2=80=99t:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As interest rates shot up from near-zero, dram=
atically improving the returns on new annuities, investors mostly stayed in=
 their existing policies, new data show. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Surrenders, or early cash-outs, from fixed-rat=
e deferred annuities ticked up only modestly last year, rising to 8% of ass=
ets compared with 7% for 2021, according to industry-funded research firm L=
imra. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CSo far at least, surrender experience=
 is running favorably [for the industry] compared to what you would expect =
in an environment where interest rates have increased this much,=E2=80=9D s=
aid Douglas Baker, director of North American life insurance at ratings fir=
m Fitch Ratings.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And some of this is due to the same sorts=C2=
=A0of behavioral and franchise-y reasons that banks used to talk about befo=
re this March:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Annuity holders typically don=E2=80=99t closel=
y follow financial markets, industry insiders say.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t think people really a=
re doing the math on the insurance side,=E2=80=9D said Greg Parady, a Flori=
da-based financial adviser. =E2=80=9CMy consumers are typically retired fol=
k [who] find something they like and stick with it.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Apollo=E2=80=99s [Marc] Rowan said on the earn=
ings call the bank-run risk doesn=E2=80=99t hurt the annuities industry bec=
ause people use these investments to save for retirement. =E2=80=9CThis is =
not money they think is accessible,=E2=80=9D he added.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe keep our cheap short-term financin=
g because our customers do not pay attention to interest rates or think of =
themselves as rational economic actors=E2=80=9D is kind of an alarming thin=
g to say! It=E2=80=99s kind of what Silicon Valley Bank told itself! But, n=
o, the <em>main</em> reasons are not behavioral but straightforwardly contr=
actual:=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many investors simply don=E2=80=99t have an op=
tion to cash out. Almost a fifth, or 18.5%, of money in annuities is held i=
n contracts with no surrender option, data for last year from ratings firm =
AM Best data show.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Even if surrenders are allowed, there is often=
 a price to pay. Annuities typically impose a charge of up to 7% for withdr=
awing more than a certain amount during the first years of the contract. Th=
ere is often no penalty for withdrawing money from a bank account.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes right if you<em> can=E2=80=99t</em> take m=
oney out of your annuity, that makes it very good long-term=C2=A0financing =
for your insurer. If you <em>can</em> take money out, but have to pay 7% on=
 the way out, that=C2=A0<em>helps</em>, though I suppose there is some leve=
l of interest-rate changes where you=E2=80=99d do it anyway.=C2=A0Also, eve=
n if you can withdraw money, you often withdraw it at market value (Categor=
y 2, like a mutual fund) rather than face value (Category 1, like a bank ac=
count), which also makes runs less likely:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Investors may face another cost bu=
ried in the annuity small print: the so-called market value adjustment. Whe=
n investors surrender an annuity with one of these adjustments, the return =
is adjusted to reflect changes in the value of the underlying bonds since t=
he contract was bought.=C2=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So the answer is mostly that there was no run =
on life insurers because life insurers have structured their business not t=
o be runnable.</p>
