<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If I borrow $100 from you for several years at=
 a fixed interest rate, and then a year later interest rates have gone down=
 by 2 percentage points, that loan might have a market value of $110: Its f=
ixed interest rate is now 2% above the market rate, making it more valuable=
. If I then run into some financial difficulties and can=E2=80=99t pay you =
back, I might come to you and say =E2=80=9Chey I am having trouble with thi=
s debt, can we work something out?=E2=80=9D And you might be inclined to do=
 something, since you are after all $10 richer. You might say =E2=80=9Csure=
 we can cut the interest rate by 1 percentage point,=E2=80=9D for instance,=
 which would reduce my annual expenses but still leave you with a $105 asse=
t. Or you might agree to extend the loan=E2=80=99s maturity or cut the prin=
cipal or suspend interest for a year or just hand me $5 or whatever. You ha=
ve done well on this deal, strictly from an interest-rates perspective, and=
 so you might be inclined to share some of that benefit with me.<a class=3D=
"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !imp=
ortant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If I borrow $100 from you for several years at=
 a fixed interest rate, and then a year later interest rates have gone=C2=
=A0<em>up=C2=A0</em>by 2 percentage points, that loan might have a market v=
alue of $90. And if I run into financial difficulties, you will be feeling =
less generous, since you are $10 poorer even=C2=A0<em>before=C2=A0</em>worr=
ying about my financial difficulties. There is less to work out: In the pre=
vious scenario, you had a $10 gain, and maybe I could convince you to share=
 some of it with me; in this scenario, you have a $10 loss, and when I show=
 up asking you to take an even bigger loss you will not be happy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/31650686.259419/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMTYvdHJhZGVycy1kby1sZXNzLWNyaW1lLWF0LWhvbWU_Y21waWQ9=
QkJEMDUzMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR=
0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTMxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB94f0f5fc" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;">  talked a couple of weeks ago</a> about the decl=
ine of =E2=80=9Cliability management exercises,=E2=80=9D and the rise of=C2=
=A0bankruptcies, among distressed corporate borrowers. The basic idea is th=
at in a world of low interest rates, a company=C2=A0could go to its credito=
rs and propose a transaction=C2=A0where the company got relief from its deb=
ts (more time, lower interest, lower debt, etc.) in exchange for giving som=
e of its creditors extra goodies (more seniority over other creditors, etc.=
). The company extracted value from the favored creditors, and the favored =
creditors paid for it by taking it from the other, disfavored creditors, an=
d it all kind of worked because rates were low and there was a lot of value=
 to go around. But as rates go up there is just not enough value for everyo=
ne, these trades don=E2=80=99t work, and companies can=E2=80=99t renegotiat=
e their debts and go bankrupt instead.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Similarly with home mortgage relief. Ben Eisen=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31650686.259419/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9yaXNpbmctcmF0ZXMtbWFrZS1pdC1oYXJkZXIt=
dG8taGVscC1kaXN0cmVzc2VkLWhvbWVvd25lcnMtcmVndWxhdG9ycy1hcmUtdHJ5aW5nLXRvLWZ=
