round-color: #ccc;"> Nikou Asgari at the Financial Times</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some of the finance industry=E2=80=99s best-kn=
own names are building their own digital markets trading platforms, betting=
 that fund managers will prefer familiar and trusted brands to the opaque c=
ryptocurrency exchanges that dominate the sector.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Standard Chartered, Nomura and Charles Schwab =
are among the traditional financial institutions that are creating or backi=
ng new, separate crypto companies, including exchange and custody groups th=
at can handle digital tokens such as bitcoin and ether.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The established companies are wagering that fu=
nd managers are still keen on trading crypto, even after prices crashed las=
t year and a string of companies =E2=80=94 including crypto exchange FTX an=
d lenders Celsius and Voyager =E2=80=94 failed.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For asset managers, the collapses have undersc=
ored the risks of putting money into businesses that are largely unregulate=
d and face questions over their transparency. Many are demanding assurances=
 that their money is safe before they start trading crypto.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You might think that the natural reaction to =
=E2=80=9Ccrypto companies keep collapsing and losing everyone=E2=80=99s mon=
ey=E2=80=9D would be =E2=80=9Cwell then don=E2=80=99t invest in crypto,=E2=
=80=9D but instead it is =E2=80=9C<em>do</em> invest in crypto, but only th=
rough like Charles Schwab,=E2=80=9D okay. Also some of crypto=E2=80=99s vis=
ion of the future of financial services =E2=80=94=C2=A0like crypto exchange=
s that combine the functions of exchange, clearinghouse, custodian and reta=
il brokerage =E2=80=94=C2=A0seems bad these days:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The infrastructure being built by large instit=
utions is markedly different to the crypto industry=E2=80=99s original stru=
cture. Wall Street executives are keen to separate business units such as t=
rading from custody, as a way to reduce risk and potential conflicts of int=
erest.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The collapse of Sam Bankman-Fried=E2=80=99s FT=
X exchange and trading firm Alameda Research, which were closely entwined, =
has brought those concerns to the fore.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Custody, where assets are stored securely to p=
rotect funds from hacks or theft, has emerged as the most straightforward w=
ay for traditional finance groups to grow their crypto presence.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI don=E2=80=99t want my custody to be=
 run by the=C2=A0same person as my exchange,=E2=80=9D said Michael Safai, c=
o-founder of trading firm Dexterity Capital, adding that the extent to whic=
h some companies did not separate such functions =E2=80=9Cisn=E2=80=99t app=
ealing, and it=E2=80=99s even a bit unsettling=E2=80=9D.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As the smoke clears, some executives see two m=
arkets developing; a shallower, retail-facing one with wide discrepancies b=
etween buying and selling prices, and a deep institutional one, where price=
s are more competitive.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Usman Ahmad, chief executive of Zodia Markets,=
 said that, as the crypto industry developed, it =E2=80=9Cmay lead to a dis=
parity of spreads between=C2=A0institutions and retail [and lead to] instit=
utions paying a tighter spread in a more liquid market=E2=80=9D.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt is going to be a two-tier structur=
e with Binance being the face of retail,=E2=80=9D said Chhugani.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is the opposite of the stock market (wher=
